metadata.name: Urbs #53
metadata.description:
Our civilization is inseparable from our cities, and this project studies what the code, using only rectangles, circles and some noise, can tell us about the ones we currently inhabit or the future ones we may build on Earth or somewhere beyond.

We may plan them orderly, but they often become chaotic due to the nature of humans and the cosmos itself, and these same forces can lead to decay, decommissioning or destruction

However, how high or low we go largely depends on us.

Features: Plan & Order, Entropy & Resistance, Decay & Disintegration plus, there are numerous variations in palettes, city designs, perspective, motion effects, project sizes, building types, lighting…

Hope that you will enjoy your mint. 
Thank you for support!

Press 's' to save the canvas or ‘4’ (or ‘H’) for a 4x HD image resolution PNG. 
Vanilla 2D p5js without additional libraries created with love for code and generative art. @Qotonana, April 2024

metadata.name: Solitude 5000 #394
metadata.description:
Celebrating 5000 projects on fxhash by releasing 500 unique editions to collect for free.

Ever since I was a child I have been fascinated by the physics of raindrops running down a window pane, picking up speed as they merge into each other, losing momentum when isolated. Implemented in 3330 hand-crafted characters of JS code. London, December 2021.

metadata.name: Broken Symmetries #1/3 #41
metadata.description:
"It was the best of times, it was the worst of times, it was the age of wisdom, it was the age of foolishness, it was the epoch of belief, it was the epoch of incredulity, it was the season of Light, it was the season of Darkness, it was the spring of hope, it was the winter of despair, we had everything before us, we had nothing before us..."
                                      Charles Dickens

This piece is the first in a planed series of three intended as studies on composition.

It is built entirely on thi.ng/umbrella libraries and template:

https://github.com/thi-ng/fxhash-tpl

Keyboard shortcuts

- 1 : render @ original resolution
- 2 : render @ 2 x resolution
- 4 : render @ 4 x resolution
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution
- s : download canvas as SVG @ current resolution; This can be used with a plotter.

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #148
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: BLOCK PARTY #100
metadata.description:
A generative algorithm exploring isometric grids and recursive divisions with an emphasis on contrasting colors.

A random rectange division is so simple yet creates vastly different and interesting outputs.

An isometric grid provides a unique perspective to the recursion giving each piece a certain depth and contrast.

When does chaotic randomness become beauty and what interesting patterns may emerge?

Press 's' in live mode to save image. Best viewed after save.

* Original code by Matt Lehoullier with p5.js
